  <exercise workspace=".5in">
    <p>
      Convert the following complex numbers into their polar representation,
      i.e., give the absolute value and the argument of the number.
    <md>
      <mrow>34 \amp = <fillin/>\amp  i \amp = <fillin/>\amp  -\pi \amp = <fillin/>\amp  2+2i \amp = <fillin/>\amp  - \frac 1 2 \left( \sqrt 3 + i \right) \amp =<fillin/></mrow>
    </md>
    <!-- <me>
      34 = <fillin/> \hspace{.2in}  i = <fillin characters="3"/>\hspace{.2in}  -\pi  = <fillin characters="3"/> \ \ \   2+2i  = <fillin characters="3"/> \ \ \   - \frac 1 2 \left( \sqrt 3 + i \right) =<fillin characters="3"/>
    </me> -->
    
      After you have finished computing these numbers,
      check your answers with the open-source software platform
      <url href="https://www.geogebra.org/calculator">
        Geogebra.
      </url> You might search for <em>geogebra complex function grapher</em>.
      <idx><h>geogebra</h></idx>
    </p>

  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace=".5in">
    <p>
      Convert the following complex numbers given in polar representation into their rectangular representation.
      <md>
        <mrow>2 \, e^{ i 0 } \amp = <fillin/> \amp   3 \, e^{ \frac{ \pi i} 2 } \amp =<fillin/> \amp  \tfrac{1}{2} \, e^{ i \pi } \amp = <fillin/>\amp  e^{ - \frac{ 3 \pi i }{ 2 } } \amp =<fillin/> \amp   2 \, e^{ \frac{ 3 \pi i }{ 2 } } \amp =<fillin/></mrow>
      </md>
      <em>After</em> you have finished computing these numbers,
      check your answers with Geogebra.
    </p>
  </exercise>
